  "text": "The spectral set of bird photoreceptors is surprisingly similar between different species. Slight changes may reflect tuning to slightly different visual discrimination tasks. Tuning like that suggested by the carotenoid-coloured passerines will certainly not be the case in birds with structurally coloured feathers that are strongly iridescent, such as the breast feathers of the bird of paradise Parotia lawesii [CITATION_1] . Its behavioural movements evoke temporally changing signals in different receptors, quite different from the spectrally more static colour signalling of the songbird feathers. ",
